  <section class="cover">
    <p class="cover__eyebrow">Massey Solar Project · companion page</p>
    <h1 class="cover__title">Voices</h1>
    <p class="cover__lede">The substantive disagreement is real, and not all of it falls neatly on one "side." Here is a representative range, in their own framing. These are summaries of public positions as of May 2026, not direct endorsements; where wording is quoted it is attributed.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Who's saying what</h2>

    <div class="voices">

      <article class="voice">
        <p class="voice__who">Massey Wildlife Conservation Committee</p>
        <p class="voice__role">Founders Claudine Bichette, Lena Vermeer, Robert Rigby · opposed</p>
        <div class="voice__body">
          <p>The project threatens farmland, the local aquifer, the Aux Sables River, and bird and reptile populations. The committee has gathered over 1,600 signatures on a <a href="https://www.change.org/p/oppose-the-solar-farm-in-sables-spanish-river-save-the-natural-spring">Change.org petition</a> and is lobbying the IESO and the province directly. (<a href="https://www.facebook.com/masseywildlifeconservationcommittee/">Facebook page</a>.)</p>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="voice">
        <p class="voice__who">Massey Agricultural Society</p>
        <p class="voice__role">Community institution · opposed</p>
        <div class="voice__body">
          <p>Among the institutions publicly objecting to the project, per <a href="https://shorereport.substack.com/p/opposition-growing-to-solar-farm">Shore Report's coverage</a>. Its concern is less about current zoning than about designation: that the township has not identified its continuous prime agricultural land (the Canada Land Inventory Class 1 to 3 soils) in the way the 2024 Provincial Policy Statement requires, and should do so through the overdue Official Plan review.</p>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="voice">
        <p class="voice__who">Deputy Mayor Mike Mercieca</p>
        <p class="voice__role">Township council · moved to rescind</p>
        <div class="voice__body">
          <p>The township's process has not adequately consulted residents or Sagamok Anishnawbek; the Official Plan may contain incorrect zoning for the site. He was the only member to vote to rescind the August 2025 support on March 25, 2026.</p>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="voice">
        <p class="voice__who">Mayor Kevin Burke</p>
        <p class="voice__role">Township council · support upheld</p>
        <div class="voice__body">
          <p>The township checked the proposal against its Official Plan and zoning bylaw, found compliance, and does not have the authority to block a permitted use. "We were elected to represent the <em>whole</em> township," he said at the March 25 meeting, pushing back on the view that the gallery's opposition reflected the entire community.</p>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="voice">
        <p class="voice__who">Former Councillor Harry Hobbs</p>
        <p class="voice__role">Former council · supportive of the use</p>
        <div class="voice__body">
          <p>Solar is a permitted use; some opposition arguments rest on misreadings of the geography — specifically the relationship between Birch Lake and the Aux Sables River — and commercial farming and forestry also use herbicides.</p>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="voice">
        <p class="voice__who">Potentia Renewables</p>
        <p class="voice__role">Developer</p>
        <div class="voice__body">
          <p>The site is outside designated agricultural resource lands; Class 3 solar is permitted in rural zones; the REA process under Regulation 359/09 will address groundwater, wetlands, wildlife, archaeology, and noise; panels are non-hazardous.</p>
          <p>The project will deliver about an 8× increase in taxable revenue, 150 construction jobs, and a $75,000/year community benefit fund ($1.5M over 20 years).</p>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="voice">
        <p class="voice__who">Sagamok Anishnawbek — Michelle Toulouse</p>
        <p class="voice__role">Director of Claims and Negotiations</p>
        <div class="voice__body">
          <p>Emailed objections raising concerns about consultation, read into the township's record in March 2026.</p>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="voice">
        <p class="voice__who">Sagamok Anishnawbek — Chief Angus Toulouse</p>
        <p class="voice__role">Per Mayor Burke, March 25 meeting</p>
        <div class="voice__body">
          <p>Verbal interest in the community participating in the project. As of May 2026, no formal Sagamok position has been published.</p>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="voice">
        <p class="voice__who">Wahnapitae &amp; Atikameksheng Anishnawbek First Nations</p>
        <p class="voice__role">Equity partners</p>
        <div class="voice__body">
          <p>No public statement specific to community sentiment around the Massey site has been issued as of May 2026; the partnership itself is the public position. Both are partners with the City of Greater Sudbury in the <a href="https://www.greatersudbury.ca/city-hall/news-and-public-notices/2026/joint-media-release-atikameksheng-anishnawbek-wahnapitae-first-nation-and-the-city-of-greater-sudbury-commit-to-cedi-participation-strenghtening-economic-collaboration/">Community Economic Development Initiative</a>.</p>
        </div>
      </article>

    </div>

    <div class="note">
      <p>Two things can be true at once: Sagamok's formal objections about consultation, and informal expressions of interest in participation. They are not necessarily in conflict — and neither substitutes for the formal Crown consultation owed once the Renewable Energy Approval is filed.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

